{{refimprove|date=July 2012}}
'''Thai traditional costumes''' vary by city and the ruler of each historical period.<ref>Silahorm, kanokporn, kanhittha et al (2007),''Thai Costume''(In thai).</ref> Thai clothes can be classified according to six distinct periods of history; beginning with the [[Tiphupa (century)|11th Buddhist century]].<ref>Bangkok studio. ''History of Thai Traditional Clothes''(In thai).</ref> Previously, traditional Thai clothes were worn daily; however, they are now only worn on auspicious functions such as [[Thai marriage|Thai traditional marriage ceremonies]].
==Dvaravati== {{See also|Dvaravati}} Dvaravati began in Buddhist century 11-16.<ref>Hanisah (November, 2007)(In thai).</ref> During this period the north city [[Dvaravati]] ruled the country. The style was influenced by the Indian style that used colored stones as accessories.<ref>Bangkok studio. ''Tavaravadee Clothes''(In thai).</ref> Men's clothes during that time the pants were similar to Indian loincloths with a silk top or no top. Accessories were golden necklaces and metal belts. On women's clothes the tops were usually one cloth brace on the shoulder or tightly wrapped around the breasts with a long skirt from waist to ankle. Accessories were similar to those of the men.
==Lopburi== {{See also|Lavo Kingdom}} [[File:Siamese Mercenaries Angkor Wat 0876.jpg|thumb|Image of Siamese mercenaries from Lopburi Kingdom in [[Angkor Wat]].]] Lopburi started at the end of Buddhist century 16-19. This period was ruled by the [[Lavo Kingdom|Lopburi]].<ref name="Baanjomyutcomaugust">baanjomyut.com (august, 2001)(In thai)</ref> Fashion was influenced by the [[Khmer Empire|Khmer]].<ref>Ohm Ratchavej (2000)''The Thai History''. Amarin(In thai)</ref> Men's clothes were short ''[[sarong]]''s worn tight around the waist about knee length with a metal belt. Women's clothes were sometimes without top or a cloth wrapping the breasts, with a short sarong. Both ends of the sarong came together in the front to look like a stripe.
<gallery mode=packed heights=200px> Image:Dancing art Thai ancient show in the Wat Phra Thaen Sila At fair 01.jpg|Thai clothing style of Lopburi period influenced by the [[Cambodia|Khmer]] [[Apsara]]. Image:Dancing art Thai ancient show in the Wat Phra Thaen Sila At fair 06.jpg|Thai dancer with the Lopburi style clothing. </gallery>
==Sukhothai== {{See also|Sukhothai Kingdom}}
Sukhothai became the fashion in Buddhist century 19-20. The city of [[Sukhothai Historical Park|Sukhothai]] united the cities which were ruled by different kings.<ref name="Baanjomyutcomaugust" /> Men's clothing was a simple full sleeved top with a long ''V'' shape neck and a cloth brace on their shoulders. The loincloth was made of silk with a big metal or golden belt. Women's clothing was a long silk sarong with flowers painted on it. The top normally is a full sleeved silk cloth. Married women wore one cloth wrapped around the breasts made of silk or other fabric.<ref>Chayada (2009),thaigoodview.com(In thai)</ref>
==Ayutthaya== {{See also|Traditional Thai clothing|Ayutthaya Kingdom}} [[File:La_Loubere_Kingdom_of_Siam.jpg|thumb|right|150px|A New historical recorded (Du Royaume de Siam) by French writer [[Simon de La Loubère]] show Siamese official wearing [[Lomphok]] and [[Chang kben|Chong kraben]], Lifestyle of Siamese people and [[Traditional Thai house]]]] Ayutthaya was the style during the end of Buddhist century 19-21. [[Ayutthaya Historical Park|Ayutthaya]] was the capital for 417 years, the longest period since Thailand was under one king.<ref>Thailand Knowledge Center (March 2012),'''The costume of Ayutthaya'''(In thai)</ref> Many styles followed the period of Ayutthaya but they changed frequently, under the influence of many countries and are not considered traditional.
Historically, both Thai males and females dressed themselves with a loincloth wrap called ''[[Chang kben|chong kraben]]''. Men wore their ''chong kraben'' to cover the waist to halfway down the thigh, while women covered the waist to well below the knee.<ref name="terwiel">{{cite journal|last=Terwiel|first=Barend Jan|date=2007|title=The Body and Sexuality in Siam: A First Exploration in Early Sources|journal=Manusya: Journal of Humanities|issue=14|pages=42–55|url=http://www.manusya.journals.chula.ac.th/files/essay/Terwiel_42-55.pdf}}</ref> Bare chests and bare feet were accepted as part of the Thai formal dress code, and is observed in murals, illustrated manuscripts, and early photographs up to the middle of the 1800s.<ref name="terwiel"/> In the royal court, royalty and nobility men are wearing [[lomphok]], a tall [[pointed hat]], made of white cloth wrapped around a bamboo frame, and [[Khrui]], a light outer garment worn as a gown or [[robe]] in certain ceremonial settings. Traditional Thai attire has changed significantly throughout the [[Rattanakosin period]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Formal Thai National Costume in the Reign of King Bhumibol Adulyadej |last=Mayusoh|first=Chanoknart|date=2014|work=International Journal of Social, Behavioral, Educational, Economic, Business and Industrial Engineering|publisher=World Academy of Science, Engineering and Technology}}</ref>
<gallery mode=packed heights=180px> Image:KosapanPortrait.jpg|The Ayutthayan official [[Kosa Pan]] wearing [[Lomphok]] and [[Khrui]]. Image:Kosan_Pan_Standing.JPG|Kosa Pan wearing lomphok and Khrui, 1686. Image:Forbin in Siamese uniform.jpg|[[Claude de Forbin]] wearing Ayutthayan mandarin dress. </gallery>
