==Rattanakosin== {{See also|Rattanakosin Kingdom}}
===Old Rattanakosin=== Early Rattanakosin central Thai dressed as same as Ayutthaya period, however, after the [[Burmese–Siamese War (1765–67)|Second Fall of Ayutthaya]] and repeated Burmese invasions, central Thai women began cutting their hair in a [[crew-cut]] short style, which remained the national hairstyle until the 1900s.<ref>{{cite book|last=Jotisalikorn|first=Chami|title=Thailand's Luxury Spas: Pampering Yourself in Paradise|publisher=Tuttle Publishing|date=2013|pages=183|language=cj}}</ref> Prior to the 20th century, the primary markers that distinguished class in Thai clothing were the use of cotton and silk cloths with printed or woven motifs, but both commoners and royals alike wore wrapped, not stitched clothing.<ref name="mp">{{cite book|last=Peleggi|first=Maurizio|title=The Politics of Dress in Asia and the Americas|editor=Mina Roces|publisher=Sussex Academic Press,|date=2010|isbn=9781845193997}}</ref>
====Men clothing==== <gallery mode=packed heights=175px> Image:Prince Vichaichan.jpg|[[Wichaichan|Prince Yodyingyot]], later '''Bowon Wichaichan''' with Old Rattanakosin style clothing. Image:Siamese boatman, holding an oar. Siam Wellcome L0016867.jpg|Clothing of Thai boatman, holding an oar. Image:Siamese men squat.gif|Thai men squat with Old Rattanakosin style clothing. </gallery> ====Women clothing==== <gallery mode=packed heights=175px> Image:HM Queen Savang Vadhana of Siam.jpg|[[Savang Vadhana|Queen Savang Vadhana]], a consort and half-sister of [[Chulalongkorn|King Chulalongkorn]] (Rama V). Image:Queen_Debsirindra.jpg|[[Debsirindra|Queen Debsirindra]], the second consort of King [[Mongkut]] with Old Rattanakosin style clothing, 1855. Image:Siamese woman portrait.gif|Thai woman portrait with Old Rattanakosin style clothing. </gallery>
=== Modern Rattanakosin=== {{See also|Raj pattern}}
From the 1860s onward, Thai royals "selectively adopted [[Victorian fashion|Victorian corporeal and sartorial etiquette]] to fashion modern personas that were publicized domestically and internationally by means of mechanically reproduced images."<ref name="mp"/> Stitched clothing, including court attire and ceremonial uniforms, were invented during the reign of King [[Chulalongkorn]].<ref name="mp"/> Western forms of dress became popular among urbanites in Bangkok during this time period.<ref name="mp"/> During the early 1900s, King [[Vajiravudh]] launched a campaign to encourage Thai women to wear long hair instead of traditional short hair, and to wear ''[[Sinh (clothing)|pha sinh]]'' (ผ้าซิ่น), a tubular skirt, instead of the ''[[Chang kben|chong kraben]]'' (โจงกระเบน), a cloth wrap.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thaiwaysmagazine.com/thai_article/1911_thai_women_status/thai_women_status.html|title= Women's Status in Thai Society|last=Sarutta|date=10 September 2002|work=Thaiways Magazine|accessdate=7 November 2016}}</ref>
