'''''Play the white man''''' is a phrase used in parts of  Britain meaning to be decent and trustworthy in one's actions.  <ref name="Complaint made over Mayor of Erewash's 'racist comment' at council meeting">{{cite web | url=https://www.nottinghampost.com/news/nottingham-news/complaint-made-over-mayor-erewashs-2217261 | title=Complaint made over Mayor of Erewash's 'racist comment' at council meeting | work=Nottingham Post | accessdate=14 November 2018}}</ref> A similar American expression is '''''That's mighty white of you''''', with the meaning of "thank you for being fair". The phrase is commonly used by natives of the [[Yorkshire and the Humber]] region. <ref>Smitherman, G (2006). Words and Expressions, Proverbs and Familiar Sayings. Word from the mother (pp. 45). Routledge: New York.</ref>

The origin of the phrase is obscure. The colour [[white]] has long been associated with purity and virtue in [[England|English]] culture, but the racial sense of the expression may refer more explicitly to the administrators and soldiers of the 18th, 19th and 20th-century [[British Empire]].

